{"id":"1209.2725","submitter":"Claudius Gros","authors":"Claudius Gros","title":"Pushing the complexity barrier: diminishing returns in the sciences","comments":"Complex Systems (in press); introduction expanded in new version","journal-ref":"Complex Systems, Vol. 21, 183 (2012)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Are the sciences not advancing at an ever increasing speed? We contrast this\npopular perspective with the view that science funding may actually see\ndiminishing returns, at least regarding established fields. In order to\nstimulate a larger discussion, we investigate two exemplary cases, the linear\nincrease in human life expectancy over the last 170 years and the advances in\nthe reliability of numerical short and medium term weather predictions during\nthe last 50 years. We argue that the outcome of science and technology (S&T)\nfunding in terms of measurable results is a highly sub-linear function of the\namount of resources committed. Supporting a range of small to medium size\nresearch projects, instead of a few large ones, will be, as a corollary, a more\nefficient use of resources for science funding agencies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Sep 2012 08:59:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Sep 2012 08:04:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-01-30"}
